In Java, this would be a &quot;member function&quot;.  So, you would have to create an instance of your object that has that main function, and then call it on that.  

Alternatively, you can make this a static function and call it from `main()` itself, which is a bit easier for simple apps.

Here&#39;s an example of a full class the static way:

    public class MyClass {
    
        private static String [] keys = { &quot;cat&quot;, &quot;dog&quot; };
    
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            HashMap&lt;String, Integer&gt; result = str1(keys);
        }
    
        public static HashMap&lt;String, Integer&gt; str1(String[] strings) {
            HashMap&lt;String, Integer&gt; map = new HashMap();
            for (String s:strings) {
                map.put(s, 1);
            }
            return map;
        }
    }

To do it without &quot;static&quot; on your function, you would have to do something like this in main to create an instance of MyClass:

    public static void main(String[] args) {
